# Pattern: external IdP (e.g. Google) for a members-only instance

Let members sign in with Google (or any external IdP) **without** turning the
instance into open self-registration. The model: accounts are pre-provisioned
(a member already exists in ZITADEL), and Google is used only to **link to and
authenticate** that existing account — not to create new ones.

All of this is identity content: configure it via the **API/console**, never
git (invariant 6). Use the operator PAT — `runbooks/zitadel-identity-via-api.md`.

## Provider options that get this exactly right

When you create the Google provider, set:

```jsonc
{
  "name": "Google",
  "options": {
    "isLinkingAllowed": true,
    "isAutoCreation": false,                       // do NOT auto-create users
    "isAutoUpdate": true,
    "autoLinking": "AUTO_LINKING_OPTION_EMAIL"     // link by verified email
  }
}
```

- `autoLinking: AUTO_LINKING_OPTION_EMAIL` — match the external identity to the
  pre-provisioned account by email.
- `isLinkingAllowed: true` — allow that link to be established.
- `isAutoCreation: false` — never mint a brand-new account from an external
  login (this is what keeps the instance members-only).

## Pitfalls — name them so you recognise them

- **`isAutoCreation: true` → "user already exists".** Auto-creation collides
  with the pre-provisioned account that shares the email. Symptom is a hard
  error mid-login. Fix: `isAutoCreation: false`.
- **No `autoLinking` → "external user account not found".** Without email
  auto-linking ZITADEL has no way to map the Google identity onto the existing
  account, so it reports the external account as unknown. Fix:
  `autoLinking: AUTO_LINKING_OPTION_EMAIL`.

## An org with a custom login policy does NOT inherit instance IdPs

If the community org has its **own custom login policy** (most do, for
branding/MFA), it does **not** automatically see IdPs configured at the
instance level. You must **link the (instance) IdP to that org's login
policy** as well:

```bash
# add the instance-level IdP to the org's login policy
zreq -X POST /management/v1/policies/login/idps -d '{
  "idpId": "<instance-idp-id>",
  "ownerType": "IDP_OWNER_TYPE_SYSTEM"
}'
```

`ownerType: IDP_OWNER_TYPE_SYSTEM` (i.e. SYSTEM) tells ZITADEL the referenced
IdP lives at the instance level. Skip this and members on a custom-policy org
simply never see the Google button.

## Callback URL

Register the correct callback in Google per the active login version — for the
forced Login v2 it is `https://id.{{ domain }}/idps/callback`. See
`patterns/zitadel-login-v2/` and confirm the exact `redirect_uri` with
`POST /v2/idp_intents`.
